l Nordic justice? And what does the legal and literary/aesthetic culture of the North mean for the concept of law and justice and for the understanding of the interdisciplinary exchange of law and humanities? The concept of law and literature as a research area was originally developed in countries of common law. This book investigates law and humanities from a different legal tradition, and contributes thus both to the discussion of the general and the comparative studies of law and humanities.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aRecht/i.d. Literatur. 4aRecht/im Film. 4aSkandinavien/Film. 4aSkandinavien/Literatur, Literaturgeschichte. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Scandinavian.2bisacsh  aHumanities.  aJustice.  aLaw.  aLiterature.  aScandinavia.1 aGarde, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHauge, Hans, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHirvonen, Ari, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKotkas, Toomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLinneberg, Arild, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarkussen, Bjarne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPorsdam, Helle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSimonsen, Karen-Margrethe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSimonsen, Karen-Margrethe, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTamm, Ditlev, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWard, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Complete English Language 2000-2014 PART1z97831102385